Let $r_{A}$ be the radius and $\ell_{A}$ the length of the wire $A$, and $r_{B}$ the radius and $\ell_{\mathrm{B}}$ the length of the wire $B$. Both the wires are of the same material (density $d$ ). Since the masses of the two wires are equal, we have
$$
\begin{array}{ll}
& \pi r_{A}^{2} \ell_{A} \times d=\pi r_{B}^{2} \ell_{B} \times d \\
\therefore & \frac{\ell_{A}}{\ell_{B}}=\frac{r_{B}^{2}}{r_{A}^{2}}
\end{array}
$$
Resistance of the wire $A$ is $R_{A}=\rho \frac{\ell_{A}}{\pi r_{A}^{2}}$, Resistance of the wire $B$ is $R_{B}=\rho \frac{\ell_{B}}{\pi r_{B}^{2}}$ where $\rho$ is the specific resistance of the material of the wires
$$
\therefore \quad \frac{R_{A}}{R_{B}}=\frac{\ell_{A}}{\ell_{B}} \times \frac{r_{B}^{2}}{r_{A}^{2}}=\frac{r_{B}^{4}}{r_{A}^{4}}
$$
But $r_{A}=\frac{1}{2} r_{B}$ (given) $\quad \therefore \quad \frac{R_{A}}{R_{B}}=16 \quad$ or $R_{B}=\frac{1}{16} R_{A}=\frac{1}{16} \times 24$ ohm $=1.5$ ohm

We are given the resistance $R$ of the wire $=26 \Omega$, the diameter $d=0.3 \mathrm{~mm}=3 \times 10^{-4} \mathrm{~m}$ and the length $\ell$ of the wire $=1 \mathrm{~m}$
We know that the resistivity of the given metallic wire is
$$
\begin{aligned}
& \rho=\left(\frac{R A}{\ell}\right)=\left(\frac{R \pi d^{2}}{4 \ell}\right) \\
= & \frac{26 \times 22 \times 3 \times 10^{-4} \times 3 \times 10^{-4}}{7 \times 4 \times 1}=183.857 \times 10^{-8} \\
= & 1.84 \times 10^{-8} \Omega \mathrm{~m}
\end{aligned}
$$
The resistivity of the metal at $20^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ is $1.84 \times 10^{-8} \Omega \mathrm{~m}$

Here, $R=8 \Omega, \quad I=15 \mathrm{~A}, t=2 \mathrm{~h}=2 \times 60 \times 60 \mathrm{~s}$
Heat developed, $H=I^{2} R t=(15)^{2} \times 8 \times 2 \times 60 \times 60 \mathrm{~J}$
The rate at which heat is developed is power.
$$
\begin{aligned}
\text { Power } & =\frac{\text { Heat developed }\left(I^{2} R t\right)}{\text { Time taken }(t)} \\
& =\frac{15 \times 15 \times 8 \times 2 \times 60 \times 60}{2 \times 60 \times 60}=1800 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{s}
\end{aligned}
$$

(i) Energy consumed in days
$$
\begin{aligned}
& =100 \times 2 \times 60+5 \times 40 \times 4 \times 60 \\
& \quad=12000+48000=60000 \mathrm{~Wh}=60 \mathrm{kWh}
\end{aligned}
$$
(ii) Cost of electricity $=₹ 1.50 \times 60=₹ 90$

At constant temp.
$$
\begin{array}{lcr}
V \propto I & V_{1}=V & I_{1}=I \\
\frac{V_{1}}{V_{2}}=\frac{I_{1}}{I_{2}} & V_{2}=\frac{V}{2} & I_{2}=? \\
\frac{V \times 2}{V}=\frac{I}{I_{2}} & \Rightarrow & I_{2}=\frac{I}{2}
\end{array}
$$
Current becomes half of its former value.

$V=i R$
$$
\begin{aligned}
& V_{\text {total }}=6 \mathrm{~V}, \quad R_{\text {total }}=5+8+12=25 \Omega \\
& \therefore \quad i=\frac{V}{R}=\frac{6}{25} \mathrm{~A}
\end{aligned}
$$
Reading in the voltmeter $=V=i R$
$=\frac{6 \mathrm{~A}}{25} \times 12 \Omega=2.88 \mathrm{~V}$

(d) $P=\frac{V^{2}}{R} \Rightarrow R=\frac{V^{2}}{P}=\frac{220 \times 220}{100}=484 \Omega$
$$
\begin{aligned}
& \frac{V^{2}}{P}=\frac{220 \times 220}{100}=484 \Omega \\
& P=\frac{V^{2}}{R}=\frac{110 \times 110}{484}=25 \mathrm{~W}
\end{aligned}
$$

